{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17621584","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17621584"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:55:55+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:55:55+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16756"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16756","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16756"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.56,0.31,0,0,0.13]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9447"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77596"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9447","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9447"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16756"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63109"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"5090"},{"type":"tags","id":"9840"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22328"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22749"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23264"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77596","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77596"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe ABO blood group system is the most important blood type classification for ensuring safe blood transfusion. Each blood type is characterised by specific antigens on erythrocytes and corresponding antibodies in plasma.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the characteristics of type O blood?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Lacks surface antigens but contains both anti-A and anti-B antibodies","Contains neither surface antigens nor antibodies","Contains B surface antigen and anti-A antibodies","Contains A surface antigen and anti-B antibodies","Contains both A and B surface antigens but no antibodies"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELacks surface antigens but contains both anti-A and anti-B antibodies\u003C/strong\u003E correctly describes type O blood. Type O individuals lack both A and B antigens on their erythrocytes but naturally produce both anti-A and anti-B antibodies in their plasma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContains neither surface antigens nor antibodies\u003C/strong\u003E is not a naturally occurring blood type - the absence of antigens always results in antibody production\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContains B surface antigen and anti-A antibodies\u003C/strong\u003E describes type B blood\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContains A surface antigen and anti-B antibodies\u003C/strong\u003E describes type A blood\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContains both A and B surface antigens but no antibodies\u003C/strong\u003E describes type AB blood\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThese naturally occurring antibodies develop in the first few months of life through exposure to similar environmental antigens, such as those found on bacteria and food particles. This explains why transfusion compatibility must be carefully matched to prevent dangerous immune reactions.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Type O blood lacks both A and B surface antigens on erythrocytes but contains both anti-A and anti-B antibodies in plasma.","ABO blood type antibodies develop naturally during early infancy without prior blood exposure.","The presence or absence of A and B antigens determines ABO blood type and corresponding antibody production."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019","Asbury C, Rieke F, Hille B, Bothwell M, Tuthill J. Physiology. Simple Book Publishing.  2023. Available at: https://uw.pressbooks.pub/physiology/."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63109"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16756"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63109","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63109"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-07T20:09:59+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-07T20:12:04+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9447"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77596"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":nu